# Frontend: Vue

## Component Patterns
- Use `<script setup lang="ts">` (Composition API) for all new components
- One component per `.vue` file; name files in `PascalCase`
- Keep components focused; extract composables for reusable logic
- Use `defineProps` and `defineEmits` with TypeScript generics for type safety

## Composition API
- Use `ref()` for primitive reactive values; `reactive()` for objects
- Use `computed()` for derived values — never store computed state
- Use `watch()` and `watchEffect()` for side effects
- Extract reusable logic into composables (`useXxx` in `composables/` directory)
- Return explicit refs from composables; avoid returning reactive objects

## State Management
- Use Pinia for global state (official replacement for Vuex)
- Define stores with `defineStore` using the setup syntax
- Keep stores small and domain-specific
- Use `storeToRefs()` to destructure store state reactively

## Nuxt (Full-Stack)
- Use `pages/` directory for file-based routing
- Use `useFetch` / `useAsyncData` for data fetching with SSR support
- Use `server/api/` for API routes
- Use auto-imports for composables and components
- Use `definePageMeta` for route-level metadata (middleware, layout)

## Performance
- Use `defineAsyncComponent` for lazy-loading heavy components
- Use `v-once` for content that never changes
- Use `v-memo` for expensive list rendering
- Use `shallowRef` / `shallowReactive` when deep reactivity isn't needed
- Keep `<template>` sections clean; move complex expressions to `computed`

## Testing
- Use `@vue/test-utils` with Vitest for component tests
- Use `mount` for integration-style tests; `shallowMount` for isolation
- Test user interactions (click, input) and emitted events
- Mock API calls at the network layer (MSW) or composable boundary

## Conventions
- Follow Vue Style Guide priority levels (essential, strongly recommended, recommended)
- Use `eslint-plugin-vue` with the `vue3-recommended` config
- Prefix composables with `use`: `useAuth`, `useOrders`
- Use `<style scoped>` by default; `<style module>` for CSS Modules
- Use slots for component composition over excessive props
